  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The arduous nature of military training and operations require personnel to encounter high&#xD;
      heat load, e.g., during intense physical exertion, particularly in the heat. These conditions&#xD;
      reduce operational effectiveness and expose personnel to a risk of incapacitation and death&#xD;
      from exertional heat illness (EHI).&#xD;
&#xD;
      The aim of this study is to examine traditional and novel risk factors that may increase&#xD;
      thermal strain and EHI likelihood in military recruits undergoing strenuous physical&#xD;
      exercise.&#xD;
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
